				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/riemann" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1787775); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1787775&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610164607" alt="Riemann" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1787775)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/riemann" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1787775); return false;" >Riemann</a></span> <span class="odate time_1607105087 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">04 Dec 2020 18:04</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4836252">
									

<p>I'm going to mostly piggy-back off the latter half of what ARD said here.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>To me it feels like the focus of this article is really on Chaz, rather than the establishment or the food. There's not a lot of time spend developing the place, or the narrator, or his relationship to food (or to being a vampire!) beyond a surface-level. There's a lot of groundwork being laid about the rules of vampires, but they're either things that the reader likely already knows (stay out of the sunlight!) or stuff that is glossed over (hospitality rites). This seems confusing at first, but I <em>think</em> it's supposed to set our expectations for Chaz himself.</p>
<p>The issue then is twofold. One, the reveal that Chaz <em>isn't</em> a vampire falls really flat. In the article we actually spend very little time getting to know Chaz - he doesn't show up till, like, 70% through, and then he's not actually present for the hunt. So the reveal doesn't really land as meaningful because the article doesn't present Chaz as anything other than &quot;chef who is a vampire&quot;.</p>
<p>The second issue is that this article is clearly intended to be a part of a greater whole. And in that lens, as ARD points out above, I feel like we actually don't learn anything about Chaz that wasn't already well established - he's cannibal Elon Musk, but for restaurants.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<blockquote>
<p>an entire race of people defined by the need to eat.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I think Chaz is the least interesting part about Ambrose, personally. Vampires are frequently defined by hedonism, but what does a hedonist who no longer can experience pleasures of the flesh look like? I would love to see a version of this article that really drills down on the thoughts and perspectives of an immortal vampire who cannot eat, and his relationship to food, time, pleasure, and the experience of <em>being</em>. What would it be like for someone to taste something for the first time in 3 centuries? How does that experience change someone?</p>

							</div>

								
					
