			<div class="content" id="post-content-4836296">
									

<blockquote>
<p>So far as I am aware, vampires only became associated with the borderlands between Hungary and Romania as a result of Dracula; vampire-like creatures are a pretty universal phenomenon in folklore, but vampires-as-vampires date from the 18th century in Eastern Europe more broadly.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Look, I establish the region <em>in the context of this article's fiction</em> is associated with vampires. If you demand that my vampire fiction is 100% accurate to the historical traditions then I'd have to remove sunlight as a weakness too<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-639993-1" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-639993-1')">1</a></sup>, since that only becomes a part of the myth in 1922. I don't care these vampires aren't accurate to folklore traditions: I'm trying to make them consistent with a reader's expectations.</p>
<div class="footnotes-footer">
<div class="title">Footnotes</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-639993-1"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-639993-1')">1</a>. This is a bit nuanced but &quot;burning up in sunlight&quot; is 1922 and that's the version of the sunlight weakness I'm using.</div>
</div>

							</div>

